# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: google-bigquery
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:google-bigquery/bigquery] BigQuery originated from Google's internal Dremel technology, which enabled quick queries across trillions of rows of data.
[src:google-bigquery/bigquery] The product was originally announced in May 2010 at Google I/O.
[src:google-bigquery/bigquery] Initially, it was only usable by a limited number of external early adopters due to limitations on the API.
[src:google-bigquery/bigquery] However, after the product proved its potential, it was released for limited availability in 2011 and general availability in 2012.
[src:google-bigquery/bigquery] After general availability, BigQuery found success among a broad range of customers, including airlines, insurance, and retail organizations.
[src:google-bigquery/bigquery] BigQuery requires all requests to be authenticated, supporting a number of Google-proprietary mechanisms as well as OAuth.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] In computing, a **data warehouse** (**DW** or **DWH**), also known as an **enterprise data warehouse** (**EDW**), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data stored in the warehouse is uploaded from operational systems (such as marketing or sales).
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data may pass through an operational data store and may require data cleansing for additional operations to ensure data quality before it is used in the data warehouse for reporting.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The two main workflows for building a data warehouse system are extract, transform, load (ETL) and extract, load, transform (ELT).
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Operational databases are optimized for the preservation of data integrity and speed of recording of business transactions through use of database normalization and an entity–relationship model.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Operational system designers generally follow database normalization to ensure data integrity.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Fully normalized database designs often result in information from a business transaction being stored in dozens to hundreds of tables.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Relational databases are efficient at managing the relationships between these tables.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The databases have very fast insert/update performance because only a small amount of data in those tables is affected by each transaction.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] To improve performance, older data are periodically purged.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are optimized for analytic access patterns, which usually involve selecting specific fields rather than all fields as is common in operational databases.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Because of these differences in access, operational databases (loosely, OLTP) benefit from the use of a row-oriented database management system (DBMS), whereas analytics databases (loosely, OLAP) benefit from the use of a column-oriented DBMS.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Operational systems maintain a snapshot of the business, while warehouses maintain historic data through ETL processes that periodically migrate data from the operational systems to the warehouse.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Online analytical processing (OLAP) is characterized by a low rate of transactions and complex queries that involve aggregations.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Response time is an effective performance measure of OLAP systems.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] OLAP applications are widely used for data mining.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] OLAP databases store aggregated, historical data in multi-dimensional schemas (usually star schemas).
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] OLAP systems typically have a data latency of a few hours, while data mart latency is closer to one day.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The OLAP approach is used to analyze multidimensional data from multiple sources and perspectives.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The three basic operations in OLAP are roll-up (consolidation), drill-down, and slicing & dicing.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Online transaction processing (OLTP) is characterized by a large numbers of short online transactions (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] OLTP systems emphasize fast query processing and maintaining data integrity in multi-access environments.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] For OLTP systems, performance is the number of transactions per second.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] OLTP databases contain detailed and current data.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The schema used to store transactional databases is the entity model (usually 3NF).
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Normalization is the norm for data modeling techniques in this system.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Predictive analytics is about finding and quantifying hidden patterns in the data using complex mathematical models to prepare for different future outcomes, including demand for products, and make better decisions.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] By contrast, OLAP focuses on historical data analysis and is reactive.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Predictive systems are also used for customer relationship management (CRM).
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] A Database is an organized collection of data that is stored and managed electronically.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] It is designed to store, retrieve and manage structured data using a DBMS(Database Management Software) for querying and manipulating the data.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] A data mart is a simple data warehouse focused on a single subject or functional area.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Hence it draws data from a limited number of sources such as sales, finance or marketing.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Data marts are often built and controlled by a single department in an organization.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The sources could be internal operational systems, a central data warehouse, or external data.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Types of data marts include dependent, independent, and hybrid data marts.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] A Data lake is a centralized repository that stores large volume of data in raw format that is processed at the run time.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] It can collect data from multiple sources such as APIs, Files, databases, sensors, websites, etc.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Unlike data warehouses, data lakes stores data is structured, semi-structured and unstructured format that makes them usable for machine learning and big data processing.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The typical extract, transform, load (ETL)-based data warehouse uses staging, data integration, and access layers to house its key functions.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The staging layer or staging database stores raw data extracted from each of the disparate source data systems.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The integration layer integrates disparate data sets by transforming the data from the staging layer, often storing this transformed data in an operational data store (ODS) database.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The integrated data are then moved to yet another database, often called the data warehouse database, where the data is arranged into hierarchical groups, often called dimensions, and into facts and aggregate facts.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The combination of facts and dimensions is sometimes called a star schema.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The access layer helps users retrieve data.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The main source of the data is cleansed, transformed, catalogued, and made available for use by managers and other business professionals for data mining, online analytical processing, market research and decision support.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] However, the means to retrieve and analyze data, to extract, transform, and load data, and to manage the data dictionary are also considered essential components of a data warehousing system.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Many references to data warehousing use this broader context.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Thus, an expanded definition of data warehousing includes business intelligence tools, tools to extract, transform, and load data into the repository, and tools to manage and retrieve metadata.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] ELT-based data warehousing gets rid of a separate ETL tool for data transformation.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Instead, it maintains a staging area inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] In this approach, data gets extracted from heterogeneous source systems and are then directly loaded into the data warehouse, before any transformation occurs.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] All necessary transformations are then handled inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Finally, the manipulated data gets loaded into target tables in the same data warehouse.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] A data warehouse maintains a copy of information from the source transaction systems.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The concept of data warehousing dates back to the late 1980s when IBM researchers Barry Devlin and Paul Murphy developed the "business data warehouse".
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] In essence, the data warehousing concept was intended to provide an architectural model for the flow of data from operational systems to decision support environments.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The concept attempted to address the various problems associated with this flow, mainly the high costs associated with it.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] In the absence of a data warehousing architecture, an enormous amount of redundancy was required to support multiple decision support environments.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] In larger corporations, it was typical for multiple decision support environments to operate independently.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Though each environment served different users, they often required much of the same stored data.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The process of gathering, cleaning and integrating data from various sources, usually from long-term existing operational systems (usually referred to as legacy systems), was typically in part replicated for each environment.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Moreover, the operational systems were frequently reexamined as new decision support requirements emerged.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Often new requirements necessitated gathering, cleaning and integrating new data from "data marts" that was tailored for ready access by users.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Additionally, with the publication of The IRM Imperative (Wiley & Sons, 1991) by James M.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Kerr, the idea of managing and putting a dollar value on an organization's data resources and then reporting that value as an asset on a balance sheet became popular.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] In the book, Kerr described a way to populate subject-area databases from data derived from transaction-driven systems to create a storage area where summary data could be further leveraged to inform executive decision-making.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] This concept served to promote further thinking of how a data warehouse could be developed and managed in a practical way within any enterprise.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] A fact is a value or measurement in the system being managed.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Raw facts are ones reported by the reporting entity.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Raw facts are aggregated to higher levels in various dimensions to extract information more relevant to the service or business.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] These are called aggregated facts or summaries.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] For example, if there are three BTSs in a city, then the facts above can be aggregated to the city level in the network dimension.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The two most important approaches to store data in a warehouse are dimensional and normalized.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The dimensional approach uses a star schema as proposed by Ralph Kimball.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The normalized approach, also called the third normal form (3NF) is an entity-relational normalized model proposed by Bill Inmon.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] In a dimensional approach, transaction data is partitioned into "facts", which are usually numeric transaction data, and "dimensions", which are the reference information that gives context to the facts.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] This dimensional approach makes data easier to understand and speeds up data retrieval.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Dimensional structures are easy for business users to understand because the structure is divided into measurements/facts and context/dimensions.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Facts are related to the organization's business processes and operational system, and dimensions are the context about them (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Another advantage is that the dimensional model does not involve a relational database every time.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Thus, this type of modeling technique is very useful for end-user queries in data warehouse.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The model of facts and dimensions can also be understood as a data cube, where dimensions are the categorical coordinates in a multi-dimensional cube, the fact is a value corresponding to the coordinates.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] It is difficult to modify the warehouse structure if the organization changes the way it does business.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] In the normalized approach, the data in the warehouse are stored following, to a degree, database normalization rules.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Normalized relational database tables are grouped into *subject areas* (for example, customers, products and finance).
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] When used in large enterprises, the result is dozens of tables linked by a web of joins.(Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The main advantage of this approach is that it is straightforward to add information into the database.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Disadvantages include that, because of the large number of tables, it can be difficult for users to join data from different sources into meaningful information and access the information without a precise understanding of the date sources and the data structure of the data warehouse.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Both normalized and dimensional models can be represented in entity–relationship diagrams because both contain joined relational tables.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The difference between them is the degree of normalization.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] These approaches are not mutually exclusive, and there are other approaches.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Dimensional approaches can involve normalizing data to a degree (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] In *Information-Driven Business*, Robert Hillard compares the two approaches based on the information needs of the business problem.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] He concludes that normalized models hold far more information than their dimensional equivalents (even when the same fields are used in both models) but at the cost of usability.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The technique measures information quantity in terms of information entropy and usability in terms of the Small Worlds data transformation measure.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] In the *bottom-up* approach, data marts are first created to provide reporting and analytical capabilities for specific business processes.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] These data marts can then be integrated to create a comprehensive data warehouse.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data warehouse bus architecture is primarily an implementation of "the bus", a collection of confirmed dimensions and confirmed facts, which are dimensions that are shared (in a specific way) between facts in two or more data marts.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The *top-down* approach is designed using a normalized enterprise data model.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] "Atomic" data, that is, data at the greatest level of detail, are stored in the data warehouse.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Dimensional data marts containing data needed for specific business processes or specific departments are created from the data warehouse.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Data warehouses often use a spoke–hub distribution paradigm.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Legacy systems feeding the warehouse often include customer relationship management and enterprise resource planning, generating large amounts of data.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] To consolidate these various data models and facilitate the extract transform load process, data warehouses often make use of an operational data store, the information from which is parsed into the actual data warehouse.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] To reduce data redundancy, larger systems often store the data in a normalized way.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Data marts for specific reports can then be built on top of the data warehouse.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] A hybrid (also called ensemble) data warehouse database is kept on third normal form to eliminate data redundancy.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] A normal relational database, however, is not efficient for business intelligence reports where dimensional modelling is prevalent.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Small data marts can shop for data from the consolidated warehouse and use the filtered, specific data for the fact tables and dimensions required.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data warehouse provides a single source of information from which the data marts can read, providing a wide range of business information.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The hybrid architecture allows a data warehouse to be replaced with a master data management repository where operational (not static) information could reside.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data vault modeling components follow hub and spokes architecture.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] This modeling style is a hybrid design, consisting of the best practices from both third normal form and star schema.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data vault model is not a true third normal form, and breaks some of its rules, but it is a top-down architecture with a bottom up design.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data vault model is geared to be strictly a data warehouse.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] It is not geared to be end-user accessible, which, when built, still requires the use of a data mart or star schema-based release area for business purposes.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] There are basic features that define the data in the data warehouse that include subject orientation, data integration, time-variant, nonvolatile data, and data granularity.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Unlike the operational systems, the data in the data warehouse revolves around the subjects of the enterprise.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Subject orientation is not database normalization.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Subject orientation can be really useful for decision-making.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Gathering the required objects is called subject-oriented.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data found within the data warehouse is integrated.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Since it comes from several operational systems, all inconsistencies must be removed.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Consistencies include naming conventions, measurement of variables, encoding structures, physical attributes of data, and so forth.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] While operational systems reflect current values as they support day-to-day operations, data warehouse data represents a long time horizon (up to 10 years) which means it stores mostly historical data.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] It is mainly meant for data mining and forecasting.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The data in the data warehouse is read-only, which means it cannot be updated, created, or deleted (unless there is a regulatory or statutory obligation to do so).
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] In the data warehouse process, data can be aggregated in data marts at different levels of abstraction.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The user may start looking at the total sale units of a product in an entire region.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Then the user looks at the states in that region.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Finally, they may examine the individual stores in a certain state.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Therefore, typically, the analysis starts at a higher level and drills down to lower levels of details.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources creating a virtual data warehouse.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The different methods used to construct/organize a data warehouse specified by an organization are numerous.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] The hardware utilized, software created and data resources specifically required for the correct functionality of a data warehouse are the main components of the data warehouse architecture.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] All data warehouses have multiple phases in which the requirements of the organization are modified and fine-tuned.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Data warehouses in this stage of evolution are updated on a regular time cycle (usually daily, weekly or monthly) from the operational systems and the data is stored in an integrated reporting-oriented database.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] Data warehouses at this stage are updated from data in the operational systems on a regular basis and the data warehouse data are stored in a data structure designed to facilitate reporting.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] These data warehouses assemble data from different areas of business, so users can look up the information they need across other systems.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] In the healthcare sector, data warehouses are critical components of health informatics, enabling the integration, storage, and analysis of large volumes of clinical, administrative, and operational data.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] These systems consolidate information from disparate sources such as electronic health records (EHRs), laboratory information systems, picture archiving and communication systems (PACS), and medical billing platforms.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] By centralizing data, healthcare data warehouses support a range of functions including population health, clinical decision support, quality improvement, public health surveillance, and medical research.
[src:google-bigquery/data-warehouse] These warehouses enable data-driven healthcare by supporting retrospective studies, comparative effectiveness research, and predictive analytics, often with the use of healthcare-applied artificial intelligence.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] Save and categorize content based on your preferences.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery is a fully managed, AI-ready data platform that helps you manage and analyze your data with built-in features like machine learning, search, geospatial analysis, and business intelligence.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery's serverless architecture lets you use languages like SQL and Python to answer your organization's biggest questions with zero infrastructure management.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery provides a uniform way to work with both structured and unstructured data and supports open table formats like Apache Iceberg, Delta, and Apache Hudi.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery streaming supports continuous data ingestion and analysis while BigQuery's scalable, distributed analysis engine lets you query terabytes in seconds and petabytes in minutes.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery offers built-in governance capabilities that let you discover and curate data, and manage metadata and data quality.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] Through features like semantic search and data lineage, you can find and validate relevant data for analysis.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] You can share data and AI assets across your organization with the benefits of access control.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] These features are powered by Knowledge Catalog, which is a unified, intelligent governance solution for data and AI assets in Google Cloud.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery's architecture consists of two parts: a storage layer that ingests, stores, and optimizes data and a compute layer that provides analytics capabilities.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] These compute and storage layers efficiently operate independently of each other thanks to Google's petabit-scale network that enables the necessary communication between them.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] Legacy databases usually have to share resources between read and write operations and analytical operations.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] This can result in resource conflicts and can slow queries while data is written to or read from storage.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] Shared resource pools can become further strained when resources are required for database management tasks such as assigning or revoking permissions.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery's separation of compute and storage layers lets each layer dynamically allocate resources without impacting the performance or availability of the other.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] This separation principle lets BigQuery innovate faster because storage and compute improvements can be deployed independently, without downtime or negative impact on system performance.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] It is also essential to offering a fully managed serverless data warehouse in which the BigQuery engineering team handles updates and maintenance.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] The result is that you don't need to provision or manually scale resources, leaving you free to focus on delivering value instead of traditional database management tasks.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery interfaces include Google Cloud console interface and the BigQuery command-line tool.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] Developers and data scientists can use client libraries with familiar programming including Python, Java, JavaScript, and Go, as well as BigQuery's REST API and RPC API to transform and manage data.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] ODBC and JDBC drivers provide interaction with existing applications including third-party tools and utilities.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] As a data analyst, data engineer, data warehouse administrator, or data scientist, BigQuery helps you load, process, and analyze data to inform critical business decisions.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] You can start exploring BigQuery in minutes.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] Take advantage of BigQuery's free usage tier or no-cost sandbox to start loading and querying data.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery sandbox: Get started in the BigQuery sandbox, risk-free and at no cost.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] Public datasets: Experience BigQuery's performance by exploring large, real-world data from the Public Datasets Program.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] Google Cloud console quickstart: Familiarize yourself with the power of the BigQuery Studio.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery's serverless infrastructure lets you focus on your data instead of resource management.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery combines a cloud-based data warehouse and powerful analytic tools.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery stores data using a columnar storage format that is optimized for analytical queries.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery presents data in tables, rows, and columns and provides full support for database transaction semantics (ACID).
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery storage is automatically replicated across multiple locations to provide high availability.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] For more information, see Overview of BigQuery storage.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] Descriptive and prescriptive analysis uses include business intelligence, ad hoc analysis, geospatial analytics, and machine learning.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] You can query data stored in BigQuery or run queries on data where it lives using external tables or federated queries including Cloud Storage, Bigtable, Spanner, or Google Sheets stored in Google Drive.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] ANSI-standard SQL queries (ISO/IEC 9075 support) including support for joins, nested and repeated fields, analytic and aggregation functions, multi-statement queries, and a variety of spatial functions with geospatial analytics - Geographic Information Systems.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] Pandas-compatible Python API, provided by BigQuery DataFrames.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] Business intelligence tool support including BI Engine with Data Studio, Looker, Google Sheets, and 3rd party tools like Tableau and Power BI.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery ML provides machine learning and predictive analytics.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery Studio offers features such as Python notebooks, and version control for both notebooks and saved queries.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] These features make it easier for you to complete your data analysis and machine learning (ML) workflows in BigQuery.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] Query data outside of BigQuery with federated queries and external tables.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] For more information, see Overview of BigQuery analytics.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery provides centralized management of data and compute resources while Identity and Access Management (IAM) helps you secure those resources with the access model that's used throughout Google Cloud.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] Google Cloud security best practices provide a solid yet flexible approach that can include perimeter security or more complex and granular defense-in-depth approach.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] For more information, see Introduction to BigQuery administration.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] Gemini in BigQuery is part of the Gemini for Google Cloud product suite which provides AI-powered assistance to help you work with your data.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] To learn how to set up Gemini in BigQuery, see Set up Gemini in BigQuery.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] BigQuery addresses the needs of data professionals across the following roles and responsibilities.
[src:google-bigquery/introduction] To take a tour of BigQuery data administration features directly in the Google Cloud console, click **Take the tour**.
