[src:google-bigquery/massively-parallel-processing] One approach is grid computing, where the processing power of many computers in distributed, diverse administrative domains is opportunistically used whenever a computer is available.
[src:google-bigquery/massively-parallel-processing] An example is BOINC, a volunteer-based, opportunistic grid system, whereby the grid provides power only on a best effort basis.
[src:google-bigquery/massively-parallel-processing] Another approach is grouping many processors in close proximity to each other, as in a computer cluster.
[src:google-bigquery/massively-parallel-processing] In such a centralized system the speed and flexibility of the interconnect becomes very important, and modern supercomputers have used various approaches ranging from enhanced InfiniBand systems to three-dimensional torus interconnects.
[src:google-bigquery/massively-parallel-processing] The term also applies to massively parallel processor arrays (MPPAs), a type of integrated circuit with an array of hundreds or thousands of central processing units (CPUs) and random-access memory (RAM) banks.
[src:google-bigquery/massively-parallel-processing] These processors pass work to one another through a reconfigurable interconnect of channels.
[src:google-bigquery/massively-parallel-processing] By harnessing many processors working in parallel, an MPPA chip can accomplish more demanding tasks than conventional chips.
[src:google-bigquery/massively-parallel-processing] MPPAs are based on a software parallel programming model for developing high-performance embedded system applications.
[src:google-bigquery/massively-parallel-processing] Goodyear MPP was an early implementation of a massively parallel computer architecture.
[src:google-bigquery/massively-parallel-processing] MPP architectures are the second most common supercomputer implementations after clusters, as of November 2013.
[src:google-bigquery/massively-parallel-processing] Data warehouse appliances such as Teradata, Netezza or Microsoft's PDW commonly implement an MPP architecture to handle the processing of very large amounts of data in parallel.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] In computing, **online analytical processing (OLAP)** (/ˈoʊlæp/), is an approach to quickly answer multi-dimensional analytical (MDA) queries.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The term *OLAP* was created as a slight modification of the traditional database term online transaction processing (OLTP).
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is part of the broader category of business intelligence, which also encompasses relational databases, report writing and data mining.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Typical applications of OLAP include business reporting for sales, marketing, management reporting, business process management (BPM), budgeting and forecasting, financial reporting and similar areas, with new applications emerging, such as agriculture.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] OLAP tools enable users to analyse multidimensional data interactively from multiple perspectives.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] OLAP consists of three basic analytical operations: consolidation (roll-up), drill-down, and slicing and dicing.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Consolidation involves the aggregation of data that can be accumulated and computed in one or more dimensions.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] For example, all sales offices are rolled up to the sales department or sales division to anticipate sales trends.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] By contrast, the drill-down is a technique that allows users to navigate through the details.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] For instance, users can view the sales by individual products that make up a region's sales.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Slicing and dicing is a feature whereby users can take out (slicing) a specific set of data of the OLAP cube and view (dicing) the slices from different viewpoints.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] These viewpoints are sometimes called dimensions (such as looking at the same sales by salesperson, or by date, or by customer, or by product, or by region, etc.).
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Databases configured for OLAP use a multidimensional data model, allowing for complex analytical and ad hoc queries with a rapid execution time.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] They borrow aspects of navigational databases, hierarchical databases and relational databases.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is typically contrasted to OLTP (online transaction processing), which is generally characterized by much less complex queries, in a larger volume, to process transactions rather than for the purpose of business intelligence or reporting.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Whereas OLAP systems are mostly optimized for read, OLTP has to process all kinds of queries (read, insert, update and delete).
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] At the core of any OLAP system is an OLAP cube (also called a 'multidimensional cube' or a hypercube).
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] It consists of numeric facts called *measures* that are categorized by *dimensions*.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The measures are placed at the intersections of the hypercube, which is spanned by the dimensions as a vector space.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The usual interface to manipulate an OLAP cube is a matrix interface, like Pivot tables in a spreadsheet program, which performs projection operations along the dimensions, such as aggregation or averaging.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The cube metadata is typically created from a star schema or snowflake schema or fact constellation of tables in a relational database.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Measures are derived from the records in the fact table and dimensions are derived from the dimension tables.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Each *measure* can be thought of as having a set of *labels*, or meta-data associated with it.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] A *dimension* is what describes these *labels*; it provides information about the *measure*.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] A simple example would be a cube that contains a store's sales as a *measure*, and Date/Time as a *dimension*.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Each Sale has a Date/Time *label* that describes more about that sale.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is defined as "a variation of the relational model that uses multidimensional structures to organize data and express the relationships between data".
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The structure is broken into cubes and the cubes are able to store and access data within the confines of each cube.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] "Each cell within a multidimensional structure contains aggregated data related to elements along each of its dimensions".
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Even when data is manipulated it remains easy to access and continues to constitute a compact database format.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is quite popular for analytical databases that use online analytical processing (OLAP) applications.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Analytical databases use these databases because of their ability to deliver answers to complex business queries swiftly.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Data can be viewed from different angles, which gives a broader perspective of a problem unlike other models.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] It has been claimed that for complex queries OLAP cubes can produce an answer in around 0.1% of the time required for the same query on OLTP relational data.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The most important mechanism in OLAP which allows it to achieve such performance is the use of *aggregations*.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Aggregations are built from the fact table by changing the granularity on specific dimensions and aggregating up data along these dimensions, using an aggregate function (or *aggregation function*).
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The number of possible aggregations is determined by every possible combination of dimension granularities.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The combination of all possible aggregations and the base data contains the answers to every query which can be answered from the data.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Because usually there are many aggregations that can be calculated, often only a predetermined number are fully calculated; the remainder are solved on demand.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The problem of deciding which aggregations (views) to calculate is known as the view selection problem.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] View selection can be constrained by the total size of the selected set of aggregations, the time to update them from changes in the base data, or both.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The objective of view selection is typically to minimize the average time to answer OLAP queries, although some studies also minimize the update time.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Many approaches to the problem have been explored, including greedy algorithms, randomized search, genetic algorithms and A* search algorithm.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Some aggregation functions can be computed for the entire OLAP cube by precomputing values for each cell, and then computing the aggregation for a roll-up of cells by aggregating these aggregates, applying a divide and conquer algorithm to the multidimensional problem to compute them efficiently.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] For example, the overall sum of a roll-up is just the sum of the sub-sums in each cell.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Functions that can be decomposed in this way are called decomposable aggregation functions, and include `COUNT`, `MAX`, `MIN`, and `SUM`, which can be computed for each cell and then directly aggregated; these are known as self-decomposable aggregation functions.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] In other cases, the aggregate function cannot be computed without analyzing the entire set at once, though in some cases approximations can be computed; examples include `DISTINCT COUNT`, `MEDIAN`, and `MODE`; for example, the median of a set is not the median of medians of subsets.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] These latter are difficult to implement efficiently in OLAP, as they require computing the aggregate function on the base data, either computing them online (slow) or precomputing them for possible rollouts (large space).
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] OLAP systems have been traditionally categorized using the following taxonomy.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP (multi-dimensional online analytical processing) is the classic form of OLAP and is sometimes referred to as just OLAP.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP stores this data in an optimized multi-dimensional array storage, rather than in a relational database.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Some MOLAP tools require the pre-computation and storage of derived data, such as consolidations – the operation known as processing.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Such MOLAP tools generally utilize a pre-calculated data set referred to as a data cube.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The data cube contains all the possible answers to a given range of questions.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] As a result, they have a very fast response to queries.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] On the other hand, updating can take a long time depending on the degree of pre-computation.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Pre-computation can also lead to what is known as data explosion.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Other MOLAP tools, particularly those that implement the functional database model do not pre-compute derived data but make all calculations on demand other than those that were previously requested and stored in a cache.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Examples of commercial products that use MOLAP are Cognos Powerplay, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy, Microsoft Analysis Services, Essbase, TM1, Jedox, and icCube.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] While ROLAP uses a relational database source, generally the database must be carefully designed for ROLAP use.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] A database which was designed for OLTP will not function well as a ROLAP database.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Therefore, ROLAP still involves creating an additional copy of the data.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] However, since it is a database, a variety of technologies can be used to populate the database.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] In the OLAP industry ROLAP is usually perceived as being able to scale for large data volumes but suffering from slower query performance as opposed to MOLAP.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP Survey, the largest independent survey across all major OLAP products, being conducted for 6 years (2001 to 2006) have consistently found that companies using ROLAP report slower performance than those using MOLAP even when data volumes were taken into consideration.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] However, as with any survey there are a number of subtle issues that must be taken into account when interpreting the results.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Some companies select ROLAP because they intend to re-use existing relational database tables—these tables will frequently not be optimally designed for OLAP use.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The superior flexibility of ROLAP tools allows this less-than-optimal design to work, but performance suffers.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP tools in contrast would force the data to be re-loaded into an optimal OLAP design.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The undesirable trade-off between additional ETL cost and slow query performance has ensured that most commercial OLAP tools now use a "Hybrid OLAP" (HOLAP) approach, which allows the model designer to decide which portion of the data will be stored in MOLAP and which portion in ROLAP.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] There is no clear agreement across the industry as to what constitutes "Hybrid OLAP", except that a database will divide data between relational and specialized storage.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] For example, for some vendors, a HOLAP database will use relational tables to hold the larger quantities of detailed data and use specialized storage for at least some aspects of the smaller quantities of more-aggregate or less-detailed data.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP addresses the shortcomings of MOLAP and ROLAP by combining the capabilities of both approaches.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP tools can utilize both pre-calculated cubes and relational data sources.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores *aggregations* in MOLAP for fast query performance, and detailed data in ROLAP to optimize time of cube *processing*.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores some slice of data, usually the more recent one (i.e. sliced by Time dimension) in MOLAP for fast query performance, and older data in ROLAP.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Moreover, we can store some dices in MOLAP and others in ROLAP, leveraging the fact that in a large cuboid, there will be dense and sparse subregions.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The first product to provide HOLAP storage was Holos, but the technology also became available in other commercial products such as Microsoft Analysis Services, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy and SAP AG BI Accelerator.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The hybrid OLAP approach combines ROLAP and MOLAP technology, benefiting from the greater scalability of ROLAP and the faster computation of MOLAP.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] For example, a HOLAP server may store large volumes of detailed data in a relational database, while aggregations are kept in a separate MOLAP store.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Each type has certain benefits, although there is disagreement about the specifics of the benefits between providers.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Unlike relational databases, which had SQL as the standard query language, and widespread APIs such as ODBC, JDBC and OLEDB, there was no such unification in the OLAP world for a long time.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The first real standard API was OLE DB for OLAP specification from Microsoft which appeared in 1997 and introduced the MDX query language.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Several OLAP vendors – both server and client – adopted it.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] In 2001 Microsoft and Hyperion announced the XML for Analysis specification, which was endorsed by most of the OLAP vendors.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Since this also used MDX as a query language, MDX became the de facto standard.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Since September-2011 LINQ can be used to query SSAS OLAP cubes from Microsoft .NET.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The first product that performed OLAP queries was *Express,* which was released in 1970 (and acquired by Oracle in 1995 from Information Resources).
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] However, the term did not appear until 1993 when it was coined by Edgar F.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Codd, who has been described as "the father of the relational database".
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Codd's paper resulted from a short consulting assignment which Codd undertook for former Arbor Software (later Hyperion Solutions, and in 2007 acquired by Oracle), as a sort of marketing coup.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The company had released its own OLAP product, *Essbase*, a year earlier.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] As a result, Codd's "twelve laws of online analytical processing" were explicit in their reference to Essbase.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] There was some ensuing controversy and when Computerworld learned that Codd was paid by Arbor, it retracted the article.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP market experienced strong growth in the late 1990s with dozens of commercial products going into market.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] In 1998, Microsoft released its first OLAP Server – Microsoft Analysis Services, which drove wide adoption of OLAP technology and moved it into the mainstream.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] OLAP clients include many spreadsheet programs like Excel, web application, SQL, dashboard tools, etc.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Many clients support interactive data exploration where users select dimensions and measures of interest.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Some dimensions are used as filters (for slicing and dicing the data) while others are selected as the axes of a pivot table or pivot chart.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Users can also vary aggregation level (for drilling-down or rolling-up) the displayed view.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Clients can also offer a variety of graphical widgets such as sliders, geographic maps, heat maps and more which can be grouped and coordinated as dashboards.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] An extensive list of clients appears in the visualization column of the comparison of OLAP servers table.
[src:google-bigquery/online-analytical-processing] Below is a list of top OLAP vendors in 2006, with figures in millions of US Dollars.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] This document provides an overview of how BigQuery processes queries and an overview of several features that are useful for understanding and analyzing your data.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] BigQuery is optimized to run analytic queries on large datasets, including terabytes of data in seconds and petabytes in minutes.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] Understanding BigQuery capabilities and how it processes queries can help you maximize your data analysis investments.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] BigQuery can help you understand your data before you start writing SQL queries.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] The primary way to analyze data in BigQuery is to run a SQL query.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] The GoogleSQL dialect supports SQL:2011 and includes extensions that support geospatial analysis and ML.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] You can run multiple statements in a sequence, with shared state, by using multi-statement queries.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] Multi-statement queries are often used in stored procedures and support procedural language statements, which let you define variables and implement control flow.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] BigQuery lets you save queries and share queries with others.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] When you save a query, it can be private (visible only to you), shared at the project level (visible to specific principals), or public (anyone can view it).
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] For more information, see Work with saved queries.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] The performance of queries that are run repeatedly on the same data can vary because of the shared nature of the BigQuery environment, use of cached query results, or because BigQuery dynamically adjusts the query plan while the query runs.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] When you run a query, you can view the query plan in the Google Cloud console.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] You can also request execution details by using the `INFORMATION_SCHEMA.JOBS*` views or the `jobs.get` REST API method.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] The query plan includes details about query stages and steps.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] These details can help you identify ways to improve query performance.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] For example, if you notice a stage that writes a lot more output than other stages, it might mean that you need to filter earlier in the query.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] Monitoring and logging are crucial for running reliable applications in the cloud.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] BigQuery workloads are no exception, especially if your workload has high volumes or is mission critical.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] BigQuery provides various metrics, logs, and metadata views to help you monitor your BigQuery usage.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] For information about the two pricing models and to learn more about making reservations for capacity-based pricing, see Introduction to reservations.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] BigQuery enforces project-level quotas on running queries.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] For information on query quotas, see Quotas and limits.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] To control query costs, BigQuery provides several options, including custom quotas and billing alerts.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] For more information, see Creating custom cost controls.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] BigQuery supports both descriptive and predictive analytics and helps you explore your data with AI powered tools, SQL, machine learning, notebooks, and other third-party integrations.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] BigQuery ML lets you use SQL in BigQuery to perform machine learning (ML) and predictive analytics.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] For more information, see Introduction to BigQuery ML.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] The Conversational Analytics Agent lets you chat with your data using conversational language.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] This agent consists of one or more data sources and a set of use case-specific instructions for processing that data.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] Conversation analytics supports the use of some BigQuery ML functions.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] Several third-party analytics tools work with BigQuery.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] For example, you can connect Tableau to BigQuery data and use its visualization tools to analyze and share your analysis.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] For more information on considerations when using third-party tools, see Third-party tool integration.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] ODBC and JDBC drivers are available and can be used to integrate your application with BigQuery.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] The intent of these drivers is to help users leverage the power of BigQuery with existing tooling and infrastructure.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] For information on latest release and known issues, see ODBC and JDBC drivers for BigQuery.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] The pandas libraries like `pandas-gbq` let you interact with BigQuery data in Jupyter notebooks.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] For information about this library and how it compares with using the BigQuery Python client library, see Comparison with `pandas-gbq`.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] You can also use BigQuery with other notebooks and analysis tools.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] For more information, see Programmatic analysis tools.
[src:google-bigquery/query-overview] For a full list of BigQuery analytics and broader technology partners, see the Partners list on the BigQuery product page.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] This page describes the storage component of BigQuery.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] BigQuery storage is optimized for running analytic queries over large datasets.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] It also supports high-throughput streaming ingestion and high-throughput reads.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Understanding BigQuery storage can help you to optimize your workloads.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] One of the key features of BigQuery's architecture is the separation of storage and compute.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] This allows BigQuery to scale both storage and compute independently, based on demand.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] When you run a query, the query engine distributes the work in parallel across multiple workers, which scan the relevant tables in storage, process the query, and then gather the results.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] BigQuery executes queries completely in memory, using a petabit network to ensure that data moves extremely quickly to the worker nodes.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] The majority of the data that you store in BigQuery is table data.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Table data includes standard tables, table clones, table snapshots, and materialized views.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] You are billed for the storage that you use for these resources.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] For more information, see Storage pricing.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] In addition, cached query results are stored as temporary tables.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] You aren't charged for cached query results stored in temporary tables.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] External tables are a special type of table, where the data resides in a data store that is external to BigQuery, such as Cloud Storage.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] An external table has a table schema, just like a standard table, but the table definition points to the external data store.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] In this case, only the table metadata is kept in BigQuery storage.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] BigQuery does not charge for external table storage, although the external data store might charge for storage.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] BigQuery organizes tables and other resources into logical containers called *datasets*.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] How you group your BigQuery resources affects permissions, quotas, billing, and other aspects of your BigQuery workloads.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] For more information and best practices, see Organizing BigQuery resources.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] The data retention policy that is used for a table is determined by the configuration of the dataset that contains the table.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] For more information, see Data retention with time travel and fail-safe.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] BigQuery storage also holds metadata about your BigQuery resources.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] You aren't charged for metadata storage.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] When you create any persistent entity in BigQuery, such as a table, view, or user-defined function (UDF), BigQuery stores metadata about the entity.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] This is true even for resources that don't contain any table data, such as UDFs and logical views.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Metadata includes information such as the table schema, partitioning and clustering specifications, table expiration times, and other information.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] This type of metadata is visible to the user and can be configured when you create the resource.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] In addition, BigQuery stores metadata that it uses internally to optimize queries.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] This metadata is not directly visible to users.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Many traditional database systems store their data in row-oriented format, meaning rows are stored together, with the fields in each row appearing sequentially on disk.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Row-oriented databases are efficient at looking up individual records.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] However, they can be less efficient at performing analytical functions across many records, because the system has to read every field when accessing a record.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] BigQuery stores table data in *columnar* format, meaning it stores each column separately.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Column-oriented databases are particularly efficient at scanning individual columns over an entire dataset.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Column-oriented databases are optimized for analytic workloads that aggregate data over a very large number of records.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Often, an analytic query only needs to read a few columns from a table.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] For example, if you want to compute the sum of a column over millions of rows, BigQuery can read that column data without reading every field of every row.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Another advantage of column-oriented databases is that data within a column typically has more redundancy than data across a row.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] This characteristic allows for greater data compression by using techniques such as run-length encoding, which can improve read performance.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] You can be billed for BigQuery data storage in either logical or physical (compressed) bytes, or a combination of both.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] The storage billing model you choose determines your storage pricing.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] The storage billing model you choose doesn't impact BigQuery performance.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Whichever billing model you choose, your data is stored as physical bytes.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] You set the storage billing model at the dataset level.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] If you don't specify a storage billing model when you create a dataset, it defaults to using logical storage billing.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] However, you can change a dataset's storage billing model after you create it.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] If you change a dataset's storage billing model, you must wait 14 days before you can change the storage billing model again.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] When you change a dataset's billing model, it takes 24 hours for the change to take effect.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Any tables or table partitions in long-term storage are not reset to active storage when you change a dataset's billing model.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Query performance and query latency are not affected by changing a dataset's billing model.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Datasets use time travel and fail-safe storage for data retention.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Time travel and fail-safe storage are charged separately at active storage rates when you use physical storage billing, but are included in the base rate you are charged when you use logical storage billing.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] You can modify the time travel window you use for a dataset in order to balance physical storage costs with data retention.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] For more information about dataset data retention, see Data retention with time travel and fail-safe.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] For more information on forecasting your storage costs, see Forecast storage billing.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] located in the same region as the dataset.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Optimizing BigQuery storage improves query performance and controls cost.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] For information about optimizing storage, see Optimize storage in BigQuery.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] There are several basic patterns for ingesting data into BigQuery.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] For more information about when to choose each of these ingestion methods, see Introduction to loading data.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] For pricing information, see Data ingestion pricing.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Most of the time, you store data in BigQuery in order to run analytical queries on that data.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] However, sometimes you might want to read records directly from a table.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] For pricing information, see Data extraction pricing.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] When you delete a table, the data persists for at least the duration of your time travel window.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] After this, data is cleaned up from disk within the Google Cloud deletion timeline.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Some deletion operations, such as the `DROP COLUMN` statement, are metadata-only operations.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] In this case, storage is freed up the next time you modify the affected rows.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] If you do not modify the table, there is no guaranteed time within which the storage is freed up.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] For more information, see Data deletion on Google Cloud.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] What's next Learn about working with tables.
[src:google-bigquery/storage-overview] Learn about data security and governance.
